\chapter{Introduction}

While robots are nowadays widely used in factories there are few applications of robots in domestic environments. One big reason for this, beside the cost of course, is that in factories the environment can be adjusted to the robot and therefore can be kept as simple as possible. On the other hand everyday human environments vary a lot and are often cluttered with various different objects and obstacles. Acquiring the necessary information to execute tasks in such chaotic environments is much more complicated and therefore usually afflicted with uncertainty. One way to deal with such complicated environments and uncertain information is to make as little assumptions as possible. For example many systems implementing SLAM (simultaneous localization and mapping) follow this approach with success. But in fact human made environment are highly structured. Common indoor environments are organized into areas with each area having one or a few special usages (e.g. a kitchen is used for cooking). The different areas are sp . By studying human behavior one can immediately see how beneficial additional knowledge about the environment can be. Even at rather simple tasks like navigating in an unknown building humans improve their behavior a lot by using knowledge about common room structures and information already gathered about the building.

